‚ÄãAs we close out the year and enter a new one, it is time to unleash your creativity with Seismic!  Seismic is  challenging you to create your best artwork by combining the excitement of the New Year with the Seismic vision.

‚Äã THEME: Reimagining Seismic
Reimagine the Seismic universe, its characters, or its spirit with a New Year's or Holiday theme.

Accepted formats: Digital drawing, 2D, 3D, Illustration, Animation.

‚Äã RULES FOR ENTRY
‚ÄãSubmissions must not be generated with AI. We want to see your skills!

‚Ä¢ The artwork must follow a New Year / Holiday theme.
‚Ä¢ The work must feature Seismic elements.
‚Ä¢ You must post the submission on X with the hashtag #SeismicNewYearArt.
‚Ä¢ You must share the X link in the #SeismicNewYearArt Discord channel.

‚Äã TIMELINE
The contest runs for 7 days .

caption:
"Vibrant‚Äã‚Äç‚Äã‚Äå‚Äç‚Äã‚Äç‚Äå Ecosystem: The Invisible Architectures of the Community"

The power of an ecosystem is often not in the lines of code but in the steps of people who are willing to write, discuss, improve and bring those codes to the future. The growth of the Seismic community is exactly the result of such an invisible architecture. Every new magnitude, every new role, every new contribution is actually the bricks that are quietly thrown into a giant structure. Everyone brings their own rhythm, their own journey, their own pace to the system; however, when these different rhythms come together, they produce a single big vibration: the heartbeat of the ecosystem.

The current metamorphosis of the blockchain world is not just a technological progression; it's a human-centric revolution. Once mere concepts, "privacy-preserving chain," "encrypted transaction," "private computation" are now coming to life with the touch of real people. The encrypted computation model developed by Seismic Systems is not only redefining privacy but also trust that is easily shareable. In this system, data is processed without being revealed; user privacy is protected in a continuous manner from the very beginning to the very end of the chain. This is not only a technical success; it is a paradigm shift which re-establishes people's trust in one another.

Major changes, magnitude increases, testnet announcements ‚Ä¶ Each of these only looks like an announcement. However, there are thousands of small moves, small works, and small success chains behind the scenes. The first message of a user when he is a newbie, the line of a person who writes to help in the middle of the night, the small feeling of pride of a person when he completes a task‚Ä¶ They all enlarge this huge wave.

And this wave will not stop. Because people here are not only investing in a project but also in their own development. To reach a magnitude 6, for another person to reach magnitude 9‚Ä¶ These are just not badges; they are traces of a journey. The future of blockchain continuous privacy, cross chain consistency, unified architecture will be on the shoulders of these communities which grow with human labor.
Every step we take today is shaping the vibrations of tomorrow. And this vibration is now powerful enough to shake the ‚Äã‚Äç‚Äã‚Äå‚Äç‚Äã‚Äç‚Äåground. 
@SeismicSys

It‚Äôs the 7th of December and I'm proudly a Seismic Magnitude 7 holder.
It‚Äôs my birthday, so yes... I‚Äôll be touching grass today, and it‚Äôs gonna be lit 

But before the celebrations‚Ä¶ let‚Äôs talk about something that affects us all:

ENCRYPTED FINANCE AS THE FOUNDATION OF OUR ECONOMIC FREEDOM

Every adult knows how unpredictable the financial system can be. One day your money flows freely, the next day transactions get restricted.

Banks introduce silent limits, ATMs run dry, and inflation hits between morning and evening.

And on top of that, every transfer you make leaves a digital footprint that someone out there is watching.

¬∞ People want digital convenience, not digital surveillance.
¬∞ We want mobility, not monitoring.
¬∞ We want access, not exposure.

This is why the move toward privacy first rails is more than a trend.
It‚Äôs the backbone of true financial independence in a country battling instability.

Seismic is architecting that independence with encrypted transfers, private balances, and secure business operations where entrepreneurs can prove what matters: revenue, stability, compliance, without exposing their entire financial DNA.

Imagine sending money without wondering who is watching.
Running a business without fearing that your financial data will be used to control or limit you.
Accessing cross border value without being tracked or restricted.

Seismic makes all of that real through TEE powered encryption, selective disclosure, and invisible computation, creating a system that works even when traditional rails fail.

Because in Life, privacy is not OPTIONAL or EXTRA BENEFIT
It‚Äôs economic protection.
It‚Äôs personal security.
It‚Äôs the one advantage that stops your financial life from being weaponized.

Seismic is not just building better fintech
It‚Äôs building the only financial layer where we all can operate, grow, build, and thrive without fear.

With Seismic, your money, your business, your life operates freely. Privacy is not optional. It‚Äôs power.

caption:
While browsing through the TL, I realized something: while plenty discuss Seismic, few really understand who‚Äôs behind it, why the chain was birthed, or why it's indeed poised to be a ground-shattering success. 

So, let‚Äôs talk about Lyron Co Ting Keh, the founder of Seismic, and the path that led him here. 

Lyron‚Äôs background is incredibly consistent. 
This isn‚Äôt a founder who suddenly discovered "privacy" after reading a few threads on crypto Twitter. 

His entire career has centered on handling sensitive data and building systems that withstand real-world pressure.

‚ÄãHe studied Computer Science at Stanford, where he was deep in the math-heavy side of systems thinking
He worked on AI and machine learning research while he was there.
After Sanford, He went to Google and focused on AI/ML and R&D.

These environments matter because there, you learn to treat security and failure modes as first-order problems, not an afterthought, and "it works in theory" is simply never good enough. 
You either build something that survives real usage, or it doesn‚Äôt ship.
 
‚ÄãInterestingly, before crypto, one of Lyron's early projects involved using ML to help diagnose cancer.

Yes, it‚Äôs a different domain, but the theme is the same: handling sensitive data where leaks simply aren't an option.

‚ÄãThese experiences influenced why he built seismic. 
The realization that public blockchain transparency is a non-starter for financial institutions. 

Firms can't risk having their internal logic or privileged customer data exposed to the world.

This "privacy gap" is exactly what stops serious financial players from moving on-chain at scale.
And Seismic is 
@lyronctk
's response to that gap. 

This clarity is also why Seismic attracted serious capital so early. 
Raising an initial $7 million, led by a16z crypto.

It was a conviction play on both the founder and the thesis that privacy-preserving financial infrastructure wasn‚Äôt merely a nice-to-have but an inevitability.¬†

‚ÄãBut what really stands out is what happened 
‚ÄãRecently, not long ago, when Seismic raised yet another $10 million, with a16z leading yet again.

That in itself is colossal because big funds don't double down lightly; it usually means they believe in the execution and see the original thesis actually playing out.

This second round was purely about making Seismic usable in the real world.
Now, the focus has shifted to the basics that actually matter: fiat ramps, crypto cards, and the kind of plumbing fintechs and users touch every day.

And that shift explains partnering with teams like Cred and Brookwell who aren‚Äôt playing with experimental DeFi toys.
They run real services, where a single data leak can turn into a regulatory nightmare or a business-ending mistake.

Ever wondered why ‚ÄãSeismic uses Trusted Execution Environments (TEEs) to keep data encrypted and not any other tech?.

The TDX design was chosen because it prioritizes speed and compliance over "maximalist purity."

What Lyron is building is a pragmatic bridge for institutions, not an ideological experiment. 

And if you take a broader view of all seismic does, it starts to look less and less like a "privacy chain" and more indeed like an infrastructure bridge.

When you trace his journey from AI research to enterprise systems, it becomes clear, this isn‚Äôt a founder chasing a trend.

It‚Äôs someone who saw the same problem repeat across different industries and sought to solve it once and for all. 
For when data actually matters, privacy isn‚Äôt at all optional.

caption:
Gmic FAM 

I did some research this morning and realized why private credit keeps failing on transparent blockchains.

Credit is built on decision-making.
Who gets a loan, How much they get, The interest rate, and The rules.

In the real world, this logic is never public  and that‚Äôs on purpose.

But on most blockchains, everything is open.

The code is visible, Transactions are public, Anyone can see how decisions are made which in my opinion I think it's not proper 

When credit logic becomes public, people start gaming it.

They adjust their behavior just enough to qualify, Bots exploit edge cases,  Liquidity gets drained, and also The system breaks.

That‚Äôs why most DeFi lending today needs heavy collateral, Real credit can‚Äôt survive full transparency.

This isn‚Äôt theory, It‚Äôs already happening,
Projects like Cred (private credit) and Brookwell (stablecoin accounts) ran into this problem 

Now am introducing to you 
@SeismicSys
,

Seismic keeps sensitive things private while still running on-chain.

Credit rules stay hidden, User data stays protected, Execution stays trustless, 

Simple truth:
Transparency is good.
But credit needs privacy.
And that‚Äôs where Seismic fits.

caption:
I recently started digging into how on-chain lending could actually work on Seismic. That question led me down a deeper rabbit hole, especially when I looked at where Seismic plans to expand next.

By the second half of 2026, Seismic is targeting emerging markets across Africa and Southeast Asia. And once you zoom in on those regions, the opportunity becomes obvious.

Large parts of these markets are unbanked or underbanked. Even for people with access to banks, the systems are often slow, expensive, and unreliable. Settlements take days. Fees are high. Credit is hard to get. Trust in institutions is thin.

At the same time, stablecoins are gaining real traction. In many of these places, they‚Äôre not just speculative assets, they‚Äôre becoming a practical alternative to local currencies.
But holding stablecoins is only the first step.

People want to use them the same way money is used everywhere else: to borrow when they need capital, to lend and earn, to unlock liquidity, to fund businesses, education, or personal expenses.

That‚Äôs where on-chain lending naturally comes in.

Unlike traditional banks, on-chain lending doesn‚Äôt rely on heavy gatekeeping. It can offer faster access to liquidity, global participation, and fewer structural barriers. Things that matter a lot in emerging economies.

As stablecoins become part of daily financial life, lending and borrowing on-chain isn‚Äôt optional anymore. It becomes the next layer of usefulness.

This is where Seismic and cred protocol fit together.

Cred handles credit intelligence inside secure enclaves, running risk analysis for both DeFi-native users and real-world businesses, using a mix of on-chain, off-chain, and real-world data.
Seismic then takes those encrypted results and uses them to structure loans, including under-collateralized lending, without exposing sensitive data.

That combination is how on-chain lending moves beyond theory and into real-world scale: privacy-first risk assessment, flexible credit, and infrastructure built for markets that need it most.


@xealistt
 
@NoxxW3

caption:
gm CT 

Let‚Äôs talk about something subtle but important in how blockchains actually behave.

Something feels off about how blockchains work, and it‚Äôs not about privacy.

It‚Äôs that using the system changes how the system behaves towards you.

The moment a wallet becomes active, it stops being neutral infrastructure and starts becoming a reference point.

‚Äî Other actors adapt to it.
‚Äî They react to it.
‚Äî They optimize around it.

Two people can submit the same transaction and get different outcomes, just because one of them is more observable.

That shouldn‚Äôt happen.
In most serious systems, visibility is carefully controlled because observation changes behavior.

Markets, networks, even experiments understand this.
Blockchains ignored it.
Everything is visible, all the time ‚Äî to everyone, including actors whose only job is to exploit patterns.

So execution stops being about correctness and starts being about who‚Äôs watching.
That‚Äôs not a moral problem.
It‚Äôs a design flaw.


@SeismicSys
 treats this as a systems issue, not a narrative.
‚Äî Reduce unnecessary observability.
‚Äî Keep outcomes verifiable.
‚Äî Remove the feedback loop where users are punished for being readable.

If blockchains are meant to be infrastructure, they need to stop reacting to the people using them.

caption:
THE STRUCTURAL RISK BEHIND FINTECH BREACHES AND 
@SeismicSys
 

Fintech companies sits on some of the most valuable data in the world like transaction histories, salaries, rent payments, balances, and identity details and as such face a structural security problem.

Lets explore!!

komentar.reply:
Public blockchains amplify this issue. While transparency supports trust and auditability, it also creates permanent data exposure,

 Financial activity that should  remain private becomes globally visible
making data breaches very very likely

Seismic is well positioned to address this, it provides private blockchain rails that fintechs can integrate directly into their payment and account systems. 

This allows companies to leverage blockchain efficiency without exposing sensitive data to the public.

In each instance, sensitive data was accessible because it existed in readable form somewhere in the stack.

Hence why seismic is needed!!!

Recent breaches like  Insider leaks at Coinbase, vendor compromises at Finastra, software failures at Lemonade, and ransomware attacks at Marquis exposed hundreds of thousands of users and triggered regulatory fallout.

Fintech data breaches comes  from infrastructure that exposes sensitive information, 

Seismic fixes this by keeping transactions encrypted and isolated at the infrastructure level, dramatically reducing breach risk and making privacy the default for modern fintech systems.
.

This design choice is strategic, By avoiding heavy zero-knowledge proofs, Seismic preserves performance, composability, and developer familiarity key factors for adoption while still delivering confidentiality.

Seismic provides strong base to protect data 
Which can bring about more adoption to crypto

How Seismic's privacy‚Äëpreserving expense splitting works:

Encrypted input submission
Each user encrypts their share before sending it to the Seismic smart contract.
Zero‚Äëknowledge proof verification
The contract runs a ZKP that proves the encrypted inputs sum to the declared total without exposing the underlying values.

Trusted Execution Environment (TEE)

Result disclosure only

$3B for $LIT is just fre*king FUD (+ Valuation Formula)

I dont like speculation around Lighter, so I decided to actually run the project math

Picked 6 competitors ‚Üí Hyperliquid, Aster, Paradex, dYdX, EdgeX, ApeX

Compared their OI, Volume, TVL, Fees, FDV, and MC

Then I estimated their FDV/MC and core metrics ratio

Based on this I came up with the following formula:

FDV = ((OI √ó 2.06) + (Volume √ó 1.52) + (TVL √ó 3.87) + (Fees √ó 15.79)) / 4

Thus Lighter‚Äôs FDV benchmarked to competitors = $4.8B

Project metrics before token launch may be slightly ‚Äúinflated,‚Äù and we should assume part of the users will leave

So the metric can reasonably be cut by 30‚Äì40%

That means instead of the expected $4.8B FDV, we expect something around $3B‚Äì$3.5B as a fair

Bonus: almost all strong perp DEXs (Hyperliquid, Aster, Avantis) showed solid performance at launch, despite airdrops and other pressure factors

caption:
Where Creation Reclaims Its Power Creative Sovereignty, Secured by 
@SeismicSys
 


Seismic dan 1 lainnya
In every era, art has pushed against its limits.
Not because creativity was scarce but because control was.

Galleries decided who belonged. Platforms decided who was visible. Algorithms decided who was heard. Ownership was fragmented, value was siphoned, and artists were too often guests in systems they never owned.

Then Seismic Protocol introduced a different foundation.

Creative Sovereignty is not a feature layered on top of art  it is art rebuilt at the protocol level. Powered by Seismic, creators don‚Äôt borrow space, rent attention, or negotiate relevance. They operate from a position of native ownership, where work, identity, and value flow are inseparable and fully theirs.

Here, creation is secured by code, not contracts.
Provenance is not promised  it is immutable.
Expression is not moderated  it is uncensorable.

Seismic removes the invisible hands that have always shaped creative outcomes. No intermediaries diluting meaning. No platforms extracting value. No permission required to exist. Art becomes self-authenticating, self-sovereign, and permanently anchored to its creator.

This shift goes beyond ownership  it restores creative agency. Artists define how their work lives, evolves, and generates value over time. Royalties are transparent. Attribution is permanent. Cultural memory is preserved on-chain, not erased by policy changes or platform decay.

In this new creative landscape, art is no longer optimized for reach it is optimized for truth. No algorithm decides what matters. No institution decides what survives. The protocol does.

Seismic doesn‚Äôt give artists a louder voice.
It gives them ground.
And from that ground, creativity doesn‚Äôt ask for access anymore 
it exists by right.

it quietly lets systems see only what they need, when they need it.

A fintech can verify without hoarding user data, 
A lending app can score risk without exposing behavior.
A stablecoin can stay compliant without turning users into open books.

Nothing flashy happens on the surface but underneath, the rules change. Privacy stops being about disappearance, it becomes about boundaries and once boundaries are native, trust scales differently.
